<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1437,690,1476]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,810,836]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Tube white, rough, with two longitudinal ridges and one peristome (
<figureCitation box="[1125,1262,810,836]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="46.[151,255,1896,1920]" captionTargetBox="[231,1354,187,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-80@46.[228,1358,178,1872]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURE 11. A–E: Serpula columbiana, from California, LACM-AHF s.n. A–C, opercula, lateral views. D–E, collar chaetae. F–K: Serpula cf. hartmanae, from Baja California, LACM-AHF s.n. F–G, operculum, lateral and aboral views. H–I, tube, transverse and dorsal views. J, collar chaeta. K, hooded (limbate) chaeta. L–M: Serpula watsoni, from Hawaii, UMAR-Poly 96. L–M, same operculum, lateral and apical views." pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Figs 11H–I</figureCitation>
), lacks alveoli. Specimen missing left branchial lobe. Opercular peduncle smooth, white, with marked constriction. Operculum as a symmetrical funnel, deeper (operculum diameter equal to half its length); funnel with 18 radii with rounded tips (
<figureCitation box="[318,466,930,956]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="46.[151,255,1896,1920]" captionTargetBox="[231,1354,187,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-80@46.[228,1358,178,1872]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURE 11. A–E: Serpula columbiana, from California, LACM-AHF s.n. A–C, opercula, lateral views. D–E, collar chaetae. F–K: Serpula cf. hartmanae, from Baja California, LACM-AHF s.n. F–G, operculum, lateral and aboral views. H–I, tube, transverse and dorsal views. J, collar chaeta. K, hooded (limbate) chaeta. L–M: Serpula watsoni, from Hawaii, UMAR-Poly 96. L–M, same operculum, lateral and apical views." pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Figs 11F–G</figureCitation>
). Collar bayonet chaetae with two sharp-short teeth and three additional smaller teeth, distal blade smooth (
<figureCitation box="[466,564,970,996]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="46.[151,255,1896,1920]" captionTargetBox="[231,1354,187,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-80@46.[228,1358,178,1872]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURE 11. A–E: Serpula columbiana, from California, LACM-AHF s.n. A–C, opercula, lateral views. D–E, collar chaetae. F–K: Serpula cf. hartmanae, from Baja California, LACM-AHF s.n. F–G, operculum, lateral and aboral views. H–I, tube, transverse and dorsal views. J, collar chaeta. K, hooded (limbate) chaeta. L–M: Serpula watsoni, from Hawaii, UMAR-Poly 96. L–M, same operculum, lateral and apical views." pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Fig. 11J</figureCitation>
). Thorax with hooded (limbate) chaetae (
<figureCitation box="[1048,1156,970,996]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="46.[151,255,1896,1920]" captionTargetBox="[231,1354,187,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-80@46.[228,1358,178,1872]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURE 11. A–E: Serpula columbiana, from California, LACM-AHF s.n. A–C, opercula, lateral views. D–E, collar chaetae. F–K: Serpula cf. hartmanae, from Baja California, LACM-AHF s.n. F–G, operculum, lateral and aboral views. H–I, tube, transverse and dorsal views. J, collar chaeta. K, hooded (limbate) chaeta. L–M: Serpula watsoni, from Hawaii, UMAR-Poly 96. L–M, same operculum, lateral and apical views." pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Fig. 11K</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1437,690,1476]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,389,1010,1036]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Measurements.</emphasis>
TL=22.5 mm, THL=2.0 mm, THW=0.6 mm, POL=5.3 mm, OL=1.2 mm, OD=0.6 mm, the radioles of right side are 18.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1437,690,1476]" box="[198,562,1090,1116]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,301,1090,1116]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Habitat.</emphasis>
Depth: intertidal reef.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1437,690,1476]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,359,1130,1156]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Distribution.</emphasis>
The nominal species is distributed in Western Pacific: 
<collectingCountry box="[1018,1217,1130,1156]" name="Marshall Islands" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Marshall Islands</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1230,1431,1130,1156]" name="Solomon Islands" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Solomon Islands</collectingCountry>
, Nouvelle Calédonie, 
<collectingCountry box="[399,464,1170,1196]" name="Palau" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Palau</collectingCountry>
Islands, 
<collectingCountry box="[569,625,1170,1196]" name="Micronesia" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Truk</collectingCountry>
Islands and 
<collectingCountry box="[772,858,1170,1196]" name="Micronesia" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Ponape</collectingCountry>
Islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Imajima, M. &amp; ten Hove, H. A." box="[963,1278,1170,1196]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" pagination="35 - 66" refId="ref35039" refString="Imajima, M. &amp; ten Hove, H. A. (1984) Serpulinae (Annelida, Polychaeta) from the Truk Islands, Ponape and Majuro Atoll, with some other new Indo-Pacific records. Proceedings of the Japanese Society Systematic Zoology, 27, 35 - 66." type="journal article" year="1984">Imajima &amp; ten Hove 1984</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1437,690,1476]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,460,1210,1236]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Taxonomic remarks.</emphasis>
The specimen agrees with the description of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reish" authorityYear="1968" box="[1028,1258,1211,1236]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Serpula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hartmanae">
<emphasis box="[1028,1258,1211,1236]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Serpula hartmanae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, including the diagnostic bulbous end of the peduncle just below the constriction. 
<typeStatus box="[968,1077,1250,1276]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Holotype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus box="[1140,1241,1250,1276]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">paratype</typeStatus>
(USNM 38400, 38401) have 21 and 18 radii respectively; while 
<bibRefCitation author="Imajima, M. &amp; ten Hove, H. A." box="[725,1074,1290,1316]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" pagination="35 - 66" refId="ref35039" refString="Imajima, M. &amp; ten Hove, H. A. (1984) Serpulinae (Annelida, Polychaeta) from the Truk Islands, Ponape and Majuro Atoll, with some other new Indo-Pacific records. Proceedings of the Japanese Society Systematic Zoology, 27, 35 - 66." type="journal article" year="1984">Imajima and ten Hove (1984)</bibRefCitation>
recorded opercula with 11–20 radii. The only difference between the specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[788,964,1330,1356]" name="Isla Guadalupe" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Isla Guadalupe</collectingCountry>
and tropical specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reish" authorityYear="1968" box="[1279,1435,1331,1356]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Serpula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hartmanae">
<emphasis box="[1279,1435,1331,1356]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">S. hartmanae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the shape of the distal section of the operculum that is not completely opened as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reish" authorityYear="1968" box="[1157,1314,1371,1396]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Serpula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hartmanae">
<emphasis box="[1157,1314,1371,1396]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">S. hartmanae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, this maybe is an artefact of fixation. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reish" authorityYear="1968" box="[588,814,1411,1436]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Serpula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="hartmanae">
<emphasis box="[588,814,1411,1436]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Serpula hartmanae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
live typically in coral reefs, while 
<collectingCountry box="[1231,1408,1410,1436]" name="Isla Guadalupe" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Isla Guadalupe</collectingCountry>
is located in a temperate system, with strong upwellings and far from commercial routes of navigation.
</paragraph>
